---
import { Image } from 'astro:assets';
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import EmailCapture from '../components/EmailCapture.astro';
import AuthorBio from '../components/AuthorBio.astro';
import HeroImage from '../components/HeroImage.astro';
import AffiliateNote from '../components/AffiliateNote.astro';
import wagashiTrio from '../assets/content/photo-wagashi-trio.jpeg';
import wagashiGreenPink from '../assets/content/photo-wagashi-green-pink.jpeg';
import wagashiPersimmon from '../assets/content/photo-wagashi-persimmon.jpeg';

const PUBLISH_DATE = '2026-07-15';
const dateFormatter = new Intl.DateTimeFormat('en-US', { year: 'numeric', month: 'long', day: 'numeric' });

const TITLE = 'Wagashi 101: The Sweets Served at a Japanese Tea Ceremony (2026)';
const DESCRIPTION = "Wagashi are the traditional sweets served just before matcha at a tea ceremony — timed to balance the tea's bitterness, with shape, color, and name almost always tied to the season. Namagashi vs higashi, kōhaku-tō, and how to eat them, explained by a practicing Urasenke student.";
---

<BaseLayout
  title={TITLE}
  description={DESCRIPTION}
  ogType="article"
  ogImage={wagashiTrio}
  showCompareCta
>
  <HeroImage
    src={wagashiTrio}
    alt="A trio of soft nerikiri wagashi sweets in seasonal shapes and colors, arranged on a black lacquer tray"
  />

  <p class="text-sm text-warm-gray-mid mb-2">
    <time datetime={PUBLISH_DATE}>{dateFormatter.format(new Date(PUBLISH_DATE))}</time>
  </p>
  <AffiliateNote />

  <h1 class="font-serif font-semibold text-4xl text-sumi mb-4 leading-tight">
    Wagashi 101: The Sweets Served at a Japanese Tea Ceremony
  </h1>

  {/* GEO answer block */}
  <div class="bg-sakura-light rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 border-l-4 border-sakura-deep">
    <p class="text-sm font-medium text-sakura-deep mb-1">Quick Answer</p>
    <p class="text-sumi leading-relaxed text-sm">
      Wagashi are the traditional sweets served just before matcha at a tea ceremony — their
      sweetness is timed to balance the tea's bitterness, and their shape, color, and name almost
      always reference the current season. There are two main types you'll encounter:
      <strong>namagashi</strong> (soft, sculpted sweets — the elegant ones you've seen in photos)
      and <strong>higashi</strong> (dry, pressed sugar sweets, often used in simpler or seasonal
      settings).
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="prose max-w-none text-sumi">
    <h2>Why the sweet comes before the tea</h2>
    <p>
      This surprises most first-time guests: you eat the wagashi <em>before</em> drinking, not
      alongside it. The sugar prepares your palate so the tea's bitterness reads as balanced
      rather than sharp — the two are designed as a pair, not separate courses.
    </p>
    <p>
      In my own practice, the rule is simple and always the same: the sweet is eaten before the
      tea, never alongside it, and never bitten into whole. I use the kuromoji pick to cut it into
      small pieces first — no exceptions, no matter how tempting a whole bite looks.
    </p>

    <h2>Namagashi: the sculpted sweets</h2>
    <p>
      These are the wagashi people photograph — soft, often made from <em>nerikiri</em> (sweetened
      white bean paste, shaped and colored by hand) or wrapped around a bean-jam center. What makes
      them remarkable is how much they say without words: a single sweet is often named after a
      season, a poem, or a fleeting moment — a persimmon in autumn, a hydrangea in the rainy
      season, cherry blossoms in spring.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="my-8 rounded-xl overflow-hidden">
    <Image
      src={wagashiGreenPink}
      alt="A pink and green nerikiri wagashi shaped like a chrysanthemum on a black lacquer tray"
      widths={[400, 800, 1200]}
      sizes="(min-width: 1024px) 768px, 100vw"
      class="w-full h-auto max-h-[420px] object-cover"
    />
  </div>

  <div class="prose max-w-none text-sumi">
    <p>
      The pink-and-green sweet in the photo above is a chrysanthemum motif — the kind of seasonal
      detail a host chooses deliberately, often weeks in advance, to match the exact week of your
      visit.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Etiquette note:</strong> don't bite directly into a whole namagashi. Use the small
      pick (<em>kuromoji</em>) provided to cut it into bite-sized pieces first, eating one piece at
      a time.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="my-8 rounded-xl overflow-hidden">
    <Image
      src={wagashiPersimmon}
      alt="A persimmon-shaped namagashi wagashi sweet, an autumn motif, on a black lacquer tray"
      widths={[400, 800, 1200]}
      sizes="(min-width: 1024px) 768px, 100vw"
      class="w-full h-auto max-h-[420px] object-cover"
    />
  </div>

  <div class="prose max-w-none text-sumi">
    <h2>Higashi: the dry sweets</h2>
    <p>
      Higashi are pressed sugar or rice-flour sweets — harder, lighter, often stamped with seasonal
      shapes (a maple leaf, a wave pattern, a New Year motif). They're common in simpler tea
      gatherings and are traditionally what's served alongside usucha (thin tea) in some settings,
      though practice varies.
    </p>

    <h2>Kōhaku-tō: the jewel-like sweet</h2>
    <p>
      The amber, jelly-like sweet you may see on a tea plate — made from agar and sugar, often cut
      into small glassy blocks — is kōhaku-tō. It isn't a recent trend; it's a long-standing
      confection with real history. What's changed is visibility: its jewel-like look has made it
      newly popular on social media, but the sweet itself has been part of the wagashi world for a
      long time.
    </p>

    <h2>What to look for as a guest</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>The shape and color usually name the season</strong> — ask your host what the
        sweet represents. It's one of the most welcomed questions you can ask (see our
        <a href="/questions-before-booking-tea-ceremony-tokyo">10 questions before you book</a> guide).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>One sweet, rarely more</strong> — wagashi at a ceremony are a small, deliberate
        pause, not a dessert course.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>The wrapping matters too</strong> — many are served on seasonal washi paper,
        itself part of the presentation.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <EmailCapture />
  <AuthorBio />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'Article',
    'headline': TITLE,
    'description': DESCRIPTION,
    'datePublished': PUBLISH_DATE,
    'author': {
      '@type': 'Person',
      'name': 'Suzu',
      'url': 'https://tokyoinseason.com/about',
    },
    'publisher': {
      '@type': 'Organization',
      'name': 'Tokyo in Season',
      'url': 'https://tokyoinseason.com',
    },
    'mainEntityOfPage': 'https://tokyoinseason.com/wagashi-tea-ceremony-sweets',
  })} />
</BaseLayout>
